A '''district municipality''' is a designation for a class of [[municipality|municipalities]] found in several locations, including [[Canada]], [[Lithuania]], and [[South Africa]].
== Usage in British Columbia == Under provincial law, municipalities in [[British Columbia]] are to be designated "district municipalities" on incorporation if the area to be incorporated is greater than 800 hectares (8&nbsp;km²) and has an average population density of less than 5 persons per hectare (500 persons per km²).<ref>{{cite web |url = http://www.qp.gov.bc.ca/statreg/stat/L/96323_02.htm#section17 |title = Local Government Act (RSBC 1996) CHAPTER 323 |publisher = Queen's Printer (British Columbia) |accessdate = 2007-07-26 |deadurl = yes |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20070708180030/http://www.qp.gov.bc.ca/statreg/stat/L/96323_02.htm#section17 |archivedate = 2007-07-08 |df = }}</ref> Municipalities may be incorporated under different classifications under the direction of the [[Lieutenant Governor (Canada)|Lieutenant Governor]] in Council, as is the case with the [[District of North Vancouver]].
== Usage in Nova Scotia == In [[Nova Scotia]], a [[List of district municipalities in Nova Scotia|district municipality]] is one of four municipal status types.<ref name=MGA>{{cite web | url=http://nslegislature.ca/legc/statutes/municipal%20government.pdf | title=Municipal Government Act | publisher=Office of the Legislative Counsel, Nova Scotia House of Assembly | page=16 | quote=(aw) "municipality" means a regional municipality, town or county or district municipality, except where the context otherwise requires or as otherwise defined in this Act; | date=June 19, 2012 | accessdate=January 9, 2017}}</ref> District municipalities and [[county|county municipalities]] are further considered [[rural municipality|rural municipalities]].<ref name=RuralMuniGovt>{{cite web | url=https://novascotia.ca/dma/pdf/mun-history-establishment-elective-government.pdf | title=The Establishment of Elective Rural Municipal Government in Nova Scotia | publisher=Government of Nova Scotia: Department of Municipal Affairs | pages=1, 2 | accessdate=January 9, 2017}}</ref> The province's twelve district municipalities were created in 1879 from six [[List of counties of Nova Scotia|historical counties]].<ref name=RuralMuniGovt/> They are referred to as [[municipal district]]s by [[Statistics Canada]].<ref name=StatCaninterim>{{cite web | url=http://www.statcan.gc.ca/pub/92f0009x/2015000/t/tbl0a-eng.htm | title=Interim List of Changes to Municipal Boundaries, Status, and Names: From January 2, 2014 to January 1, 2015 (Table A: Census subdivision types by province and territory, as of January 1, 2015) | publisher=Statistics Canada | accessdate=January 9, 2017}}</ref>
== Usage in Ontario == Currently, only one district municipality exists in [[Ontario]] &ndash; [[District Municipality of Muskoka]]. It was formerly a [[Districts#Ontario|district]], but has undergone heavy [[urbanization]] and [[real estate developer|development]], particularly from [[tourism]], as it is the heart of Ontario's [[cottage country]]. As a result, it was "upgraded" from a district (such as neighbouring [[Parry Sound District, Ontario|Parry Sound District]]) to having powers similar to a [[regional municipality]], such as [[York Regional Municipality]].
== Usage in South Africa == In [[South Africa]], [[Districts of South Africa|district]] municipalities are administrative divisions of a province. South Africa recognizes three types of municipality; metropolitan, district and local. [[District municipality (South Africa)|District municipalities]] are made up of a number of local municipalities. The vast majority of land consists of district municipalities, with metropolitan municipalities being reserved for large cities and the areas around them. There are eight metropolitan municipalities, and 44 district municipalities subdivided into 226 local municipalities.
