{{About|the fictional place|the community in Missouri|Olinger, Missouri|the community in Virginia|Olinger, Virginia}}
{{Unreferenced stub|auto=yes|date=December 2009}}
'''Olinger, Pennsylvania''' is a [[rural]] [[List of fictional towns in literature|fictional town]] in the southeastern part of the state that serves as the setting for several [[Short story|short stories, such as "The Alligators"]] and one [[novel]] (''[[The Centaur]]'') by American writer [[John Updike]].  It is based on Updike’s boyhood town of [[Shillington, Pennsylvania]].

The small town’s residents are primarily [[Protestantism|Protestant]] and of [[Germans|German]] descent and many of them live in [[Middle class|middle-class]] brick houses.  Olinger is a suburb of [[Brewer, Pennsylvania]] (itself based on [[Reading, Pennsylvania|Reading]]) and it is home to a box factory and a [[hosiery]] mill.

There is a real place called Olinger, an unincorporated town in Lee County, Virginia. It sits along the north fork of the Powell River and is located in the Yokam District of the county. It is named for a Confederate Civil War commander. {{Relevance-inline|date=March 2014|reason=Apparently about a real town in Virginia, not a fictional town in Pennsylvania}}


